From: wpp@marie.physik.tu-berlin.de (Kai Petzke)
Subject: Re: Lots more stats in /proc aka /proc/loadavg
Date: 6 Dec 1993 17:00:40 GMT

In <1993Dec6.145521.21939@dcs.warwick.ac.uk> wos@dcs.warwick.ac.uk (Will Smith) writes:

>I have written patches to Linux to include 

>       o       /proc/swapavg (number of pages swapped per second) 
>       o       /proc/bufavg (number of disk reads and cache hits).  

>They both have 1, 5 and 15 minute decaying averages, like loadavg.

>My questions are:

>Does this sound useful to other people, and would a plethora of other
>similar statistics soon appear?

Statistics are lots of fun, and it may be interesting, how swapping
activity gets high, when you start gcc under X windows, with only
4 MB of RAM.  However, xload may gets slow displaying the results,
because it is involved in paging itself :-)

Other interesting things would be (my point of view):
- a monitor of buffer cache hit/miss ratio.
- a monitor of buffers getting dirty


Every of these slows done the kernel, though.  If possible, add

        #ifdef CONFIG_EXTENDED_STATS
        ...
        #endif

around your code.  You can use the patch command to do this for
you.

>Should I make a separate /proc/stats
>directory and put the statistics there, add some more stats (what would
>be good?) then post the diffs?  

I would not bother about where you put them in the /proc tree -
people will tell you, if you made a bad choice.  Please leave
/proc/loadavg where it is, because several programms expect it
there.  If you create a /proc/stats directory, you could make
/proc/stats/loadavg be the same as /proc/loadavg.


--
Kai
wpp@marie.physik.tu-berlin.de
Advertisement by Microsoft in a well-known German magazine:
        If you don't like our programmes, than make your own ones.
However, they expect you to use Microsoft products for this -:)

